Introduction¶

This dataset contains 113,937 loans with 81 variables on each loan, including loan amount, borrower rate (or interest rate), curent loan status, borrower income, and many others.

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

There are 113,937 loans records with 81 columns. Most of the variables are numeric in nature; mostly float64 datatypes (50), int64(11), object(17) and bool(3). There are some missing data on some variables, and not all variables will be significant for my analysis.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

What factors affect a loan's outcome status?

Are there differences between loans depending on how large the original loan amount was?

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

I expect the LoanStatus to be the strongest variable that will support my investigation in determing factors that affect outcome of loan status.

I also think LoanOriginalAmount will play an important role in supporting my investigation for analyzing differences between loans.

Defining functions for chart plots¶
In [71]:
def countplot(data, x = 'x', order = ''):
    plt.figure(figsize = [20,6])
    base_color = sb.color_palette()[0]
    return sb.countplot(data = data, x = x, color = base_color, order = order)


def countplot_sub(data, x = 'x', order = 'order'):
    base_color = sb.color_palette()[0]
    return sb.countplot(data = data, x = x, color = base_color, order = order)

# function to plot sub_plots for the different datasets to some variables
def sub_plot(df):
    plt.figure(figsize = [20,5])

    plt.subplot(1,5,1)
    countplot_sub(df, 'EmploymentStatus',  order = employ_order)
    plt.xticks(rotation = 90)

    plt.subplot(1,5,2)
    countplot_sub(df, 'Term', order = term_order)

    plt.subplot(1,5,3)
    countplot_sub(df, 'IncomeRange', order = income_order)
    plt.xticks(rotation = 90)

    plt.subplot(1,5,4)
    countplot_sub(df, 'IsBorrowerHomeowner', order = None)

    plt.subplot(1,5,5)
    return countplot_sub(df, 'IncomeVerifiable', order = None)

Defining functions for chart¶

In [78]:
def violinplot(data, x = 'x', y = ''):
    plt.figure(figsize = [20,5])
    base_color = sb.color_palette()[0]
    return sb.violinplot(data = data, x = x, y = y, color = base_color)

def boxplot(data, x = 'x', y = ''):
    plt.figure(figsize = [20,5])
    base_color = sb.color_palette()[0]
    return sb.boxplot(data = data, x = x, y = y, color = base_color);

def barplot(data, x = 'x', y = '', order = ''):
    plt.figure(figsize = [20,5])
    base_color = sb.color_palette()[0]
    return sb.barplot(data = data, x = x, y = y, color = base_color, order = order);

def bivariate_count(data, x = 'x', hue = 'y'):
    plt.figure(figsize = [20, 5])
    order = loans['LoanStatus'].value_counts().index
    base_color = sb.color_palette()[0]
    plt.xticks(rotation = 45)
    return sb.countplot(data = loans, x= x, hue = hue, order = order);

Conclusions¶

At the end of this investigation, my findings are:

  • State with the name CA has the highest number of borrowers
  • There are more borrowers with StatedMonthlyIncome between 4000 to 6500
  • The LoanOriginalAmount are more of 5000, 10000, 15000
  • There are more of borrower with EmploymentStatus of Employed and Full-time
  • The LoanStatus is high on Current and Completed
  • More borrowers at Term 36
  • The borrowers occupation indicated more as 'Other' or 'Professional' The findings above were discovered mostly by the use of univariate plotting.

My main features of interest are:

  • What factors affect a loan's outcome status? The IncomeRange and EmploymentStatus are strong factors that affects the outcome of loans. It is observed that IncomeRange of 25,000 - 49,999 and 50,000 - 74,9999 varies mostly with the LoanStatus. Also, the EmploymentStatus of Employed and Full-time show strong variation with the LoanStatus, especially in the category of completed loans and current loans.

These findings were resolved using both univariate and bivariate plot.(Univariate subplot of EmploymentStatus for the different LoanStatus category datasets and bivariate barplot of LoanStatus and IncomeRange)

  • Are there differences between loans depending on how large the original loan amount was? There exists a difference in LoanOriginalAmount depending on the size. for large size loans, the Term for the loan is always high (Term 60). The LoanStatus for this large loans is more on the current LoanStatus.

The findings were discovered from the bivariate violinplot of LoanOriginalAmount and Term, and also the bivariate boxplot of LoanOriginalAmount and LoanStatus.
